    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.24.9a-9c_0001"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Neihardt Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">9a</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <add>124 23, University <unclear>St.</unclear></add>
                
                        Vermillion So. Dakota
                        June 26 '56
                    </dateline>
                
                    <salute>My dear Mr. Neihardt:&#8212;</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I now have before me a letter dated Jan 23 '21 and signed Jno <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt and addressed to me.</p>
                
                <p>It reads:&#8212; "My reading trip ended two days ago, and since I reached home I have been examining my new <unclear>riches</unclear>. I found as many perhaps as half a dozen fine spirits along the way, and I have a way of hoarding the memories of such. Your<sic>You</sic> are one of these and I am writing this solely for the pleasure of telling you that the memory of your face and of your generous words makes me stronger.</p>
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.24.9a-9c_0002"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">9b</fw>
                
                <p>I have never forgotten you. I found by consulting my encyclopedia that you are 20 years younger than I: Poets and <sic>and</sic> admirers of poets and lovers of poetry must live long. Your recognition of me by putting me in that class makes me indebted to you and I am sure I owe you this letter I found in "Who's Who" your address and I hail Nebraska's Sweet Singer. For I remember you as honoring Nebraskans in those days by your residence there</p>
                
                <p>You addressed <add>me</add> as a "Dean" I am still a Dean Emeritus. But until two years ago I was teaching in the University of So Dak. I began teaching here in 1887. I may be teaching again here
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.24.9a-9c_0003"/>
                   
                <fw type="curatorial">9c</fw>
                
                    I have a message for the <hi rend="underline">alarmed</hi> people of to-day. My message is based on the poetry that is in my soul. I am feeling a new birth of the spirit that has always inspired me. Every response of my colleagues to me, my friends tell me, makes my face look distinctly younger. I can't imagine their saying anything more agreeable.</p>
                    
                <p>I await expectantly for a letter from <del><unclear>me</unclear></del><add>you</add> assuring me of your continued good health and in any case I will be assured of the continued vitality of your great gift.</p>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
